Text.Value: Although, it not being personal doesn't change how shafted you'll be.
FINE! Have it your way! No appreciation of art, these bloody arm-havers.
Leave.
Force the printing press open and clear the loaded headline.
Will require a delicate touch to spruce up. Think I'll need my number seven pen. Real sharp.
Hurry up, then!
Then get out my way. I need to clear my reputation.
I'm not trapped, you fool. This printing machine is just marvellous. We've nothing like it in the Feywild.
Wouldn't changing the article be delightfully naughty?
Are you a talking printer?
How do you know Dolly?
Now scram it. One mistake and the reputation of Baldur's Mouth Gazette crumbles to dust.
You know, there's some absolute filth about you in tomorrow's edition. Seeing as you were kind enough to free Dolly, how's about I do you a favour?
What does Ettvard have against me?
Think you're clever? It takes a lot of craft to write trash this good.
How do we do that?
Too bad Ettvard will never get to enjoy it - I killed him.
It was surely fun while it lasted - but looks like the late Lord Gortash has nabbed your headline spot.
*There is a brief, disgruntled huff, then no more noises from the fey creature. It seems you are on your own.*
I don't want to meddle with the paper.
I'm afraid I can't help you. I've got a good thing going here - letting you swap out a whole article might get Ettvard suspicious.
*You fumble unsuccessfully with the printer and hear a loud thud. The machine leaps into life, printing whatever was already inside.*

Text.Value: Leave.
*A familiar magic dances around the printer, reminiscent of your own hag-touched eye. A fey creature resides within the machine.*
Where can I find the stuff to print a new broadsheet?
Force the printing press open and clear the loaded headline.
Reach inside and carefully remove the loaded headline.
Dislodge the current headline with a precise flick of the wrist.
Ohoho... You've returned. Ready to sow some discord?
The absolute cheek!
Wrench the printing press open and rip out the loaded headline.
I'm actually a great admirer of your work - may I see?
I need to change an article in the next edition.
Now, I'm not sure you could get me out of here, but I'm not taking any bloody chances.
As it happens, the next edition has an article about you. Ooh, it's a mean one, too - real nasty. Ettvard must really have it out for you. Hard luck.
BORING. You deserve exactly what Ettvard prints about you - I might even add a footnote about you having the clap.
Take another step further.
A talking printer? Fey magic never ceases to amaze.
All right, all right! No need for violence.
I have an article. Let's get started.
Check the headline currently in the printer.
You lie worse than Ettvard spells. If you care so much, change them yourself. I have work to do.
Reach inside and carefully remove the loaded headline.
*The smell of hot ink and whirr of machinery fills your senses as you approach the Baldur's Mouth printworks.*

Text.Value: Leave.
Quite right - miss one word in a contract and everything can go wrong. It's so to meet a fellow wordsmith.
I agree. The right words at the right time - literal magic. We're alike, you and I.
Well, first, I've got to release the old, nasty top story. Oooh, there. Now, you've got to find a new article to replace it.

Text.Value: Load another headline in to the printer.
I'm warning you, fleshlet!
*The printing press whirrs furiously - hopefully Gortash's death will take your spot in the headlines.*
There's an article about me in the next edition - I need to stop it printing.
A-ha! A meddler after my own heart - wonderful.
You need to stop it from being printed.
Am I going mad or are you a talking printer?
I'd love to see an example of your work.
Oho... really? There was that rather defamatory headline... Yes, I see the resemblance.
*The Mouth's next edition appears to be led by a piece commemorating the late Lord Gortash.*
*Your attention is drawn to a metal block loaded into a slot labelled 'Headline Article'.*
Are you addled in the head? I am no chattering contraption, I am a person. An artist. Name's Jelliwig.
*As you get closer to the printworks, something odd happens. You hear it speak.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player walks towards the imposing printer, rumbling away.

Text.Value: Oi, gormless - not one step further! You are interrupting art.

EditorData.NodeContext: the printer whispers this to itself

Text.Value: Paper's printing right now, pal. Should be on the streets tomorrow.
I may not like you, but I loved the look Ettvard had on his face when he saw the broadsheet. Well played, mortal.
Listen, mate. I'm already doing you a favour. I'm sure you can figure it out yourself.
Absolutely.
Do it, you stupid creature. Unless you want to be ripped apart, piece by piece?
How delightful.
Reach inside and carefully remove the loaded headline.
*You approach the printer, noting its ink splots and intricate cogs. Before you can get closer, however, it begins to speak.*

Text.Value: Take one step further.
It'll suck to be you tomorrow, mate.
*The printing press is running at full tilt. You don't see any way to interfere with it now without losing several fingers.*
My art! I'm an artiste. Name's Jelliwig.
Leave.
*The printer whirrs, ready to print an edition with the currently loaded headline.*

Text.Value: We both love cheeky words. She does all the shouting, I do the writing.
Ahah, someone who appreciates the art of words. And a celebrity to boot. You'll enjoy this.
As the old saying goes: 'Ours is not to wonder why, ours is but to print or die.' Or something like that.
Sounds good to me.
Leave.
Maybe you could do me a favour and stop the presses? Change the article?
*The machine whirrs noisily as your broadsheet prints.*
Where's your gazette's Golden Quill Award for Truth and Excellence? Don't have one? Bloody thought not.
I'll get on with finding an article.
Oi! Gormless! Over here. Thought I recognised you. Dolly Dolly Dolly was right - you aren't much of a looker.
Help me change the article or I'll banish you from the printer.
What reputation?
This is my paintbrush. I make sure everything that's in those big ugly article blocks becomes fine printed artistry. I'm a master pensman, I am.
Ohohoho... Ettvard was fuming this morn... What a grand jape. It's best we lie low for a while, though - don't want him figuring us out.
I wouldn't take it too personal. Ettvard gets his lines from up top, then gets all worked up over it.
You would twist my love of mischief-making for your own perverse needs? Despicable.
Right. Let's get this article nice and loose... There. You'll need to find a replacement piece, of course. Make sure it's a good one.
